Conclusions 
sec:conclusion 
In this paper we have introduced the extension of the Veneziano-Yankielowicz
effective action to a non-local action. Our modification affects the
non-holomorphic parts (Ka hler potential) of the action only: While the
Ka hler metric from the Veneziano-Yankielowicz
effective action is solely a function of the gluino-condensate, our
Ka hler potential includes terms in the gluon-condensate (the "auxiliary"
field  of the effective superfield) as well. As a consequence the
effective potential depends on infinitely many coupling constants related to arbitrary powers in  and . As the
superpotential is unchanged compared to the Veneziano-Yankielowicz action, our
extension is complementary to recent investigations on the holomorphic terms
that build on the work by Dijkgraaf and Vafa
Dijkgraaf:2002fc,Dijkgraaf:2002vw,Dijkgraaf:2002dh,Dijkgraaf:2002xd .

The main characteristics of our effective action are:
enumerate 
The "auxiliary" field  is promoted to an independent physical
  field. To obtain the spectrum of the theory it is not getting
  eliminated. Consequently, the spectrum of our model contains two complex
  scalars  and  and one spinor .  is interpreted with the
  glue-ball and the new dynamical effects represent the consequence of the
  formation of a massive spectrum in the boson sector.
To arrive at a consistent formulation of point 1, the "upside-down"
  potential for  in the Veneziano-Yankielowicz Lagrangian 
 has to be replaced. The correct potential must have a minimum in 
  instead of a maximum. Technically this is done by formulating the effective
  potential in terms of the two fields  and 
 ( denotes the effective glue-ball superfield).
The spectrum of the theory does not follow from the superpotential, but
  from the generalized Ka hler potential. The superpotential as a
  holomorphic function in the fields never defines stable couplings in the
  complex fields. If the highest components of the chiral fields are
  auxiliary, stable couplings are obtained after eilimination of these
  fields. As our action does not allow this elimination, the Ka hler
  potential must adopt the role of the superpotential. This is possible due to
  its the rich structure. The superpotential
  reduces to the generator of the anomalies (WZW-term) and has no dominant
  influence on the spectrum.
Supersymmetry breaks dynamically. There are three different ways to
  establish this result:
  enumerate 
  A strict proof of the statement follows from the symmetries of the
    effective potential: The first variation of the effective potential with respect to
     is equivalent to the mass of . Thus the mass of  is
    identically zero in the minimum and must be interpreted as a Goldstino
    mode.
  The Veneziano-Yankielowicz Lagrangian has a supersymmetric maximum in
    the "auxiliary"-field potential (the supersymmetric vacua in the
    interpretation of ref. veneziano82 ). As the  Veneziano-Yankielowicz Lagrangian is complete up
    to order  in the "auxiliary"-field potential, the maximum cannot
    be turned into a minimum. Thus the minimum must be at a different
    value of , .
   plays an important role in the dynamics. Due to this
    vacuum expectation value, new terms including explicit space-time
    derivatives follow. These terms can be important to stabilize
    the dynamics around the correct ground-state.
  enumerate 
  The breaking-mechanism is of essentially non-perturbative nature and is not
  excluded by different contrarian results (Instanton calculations, Witten
  index etc.).
Any ground-state of the effective potential can be endowed with
  stable dynamics. This includes terms of arbitrary order in the momentum
  (non-local effective action).
enumerate 

Though we are convinced that our effective action can answer several open
questions about the non-perturbative dynamics of SYM theories different
problems remain. First we have addressed in this work the invariant
terms of the action, only. Especially when considering non-vanishing values of
the source-extension this is not sufficient. Thus we should include the
complete (anomalous) symmetry structure of the effective action for local
couplings as well as for soft supersymmetry breaking. Recent results from
perturbation theorykraus01,kraus01:3,Kraus:2002nu  suggest that this
extension is closely related to the breaking of holomorphic dependence by
quantum corrections. As the impact of non-holomorphic contributions to the
potential is certainly a main result of our calculations,  a
better understanding of these terms could be of main importance. Finally, we
have shown that the semi-classical analysis of SYM theories as instanton
calculations deal with an expansion around an unstable state. Classical field
configurations responsible for the correct ground-state are unknown, but these field
configurations should be related to the glue-ball dynamics. It would be very
interesting to investigate this questions, which could be helpful to
understand the non-perturbative dynamics of non-supersymemtric gauge-theories
as well.









Non-Local Effective Action of SYM 
sec:construction 

As outlined above the extension of the Veneziano-Yankielowicz Lagrangian to a
non-local model with dynamical "auxiliary" field changes its fundamental
properties. Thus the explicit form of such an extension must be studied, even
if most of the terms will be unimportant in any application. To this end, a
more rigorous definition of the object discussed here should be given first.

Definition and Symmetries of the Action 
sec:constructionone 

In this work we consider a first step in the discussion of non-perturbative SYM
theories. It consists in finding the correct ground-state. The latter is
defined as a thermodynamical limiting process of the
quantum effective action leading to the minimum of the effective potential
(see sect. 2 of ref. bergamin01  and references therein). Thus a quantum effective action
must be defined, where the components of  represent the classical
fields. A quantum effective action with this field content is obtained by extending the complex coupling
constant  to a chiral superfield of sourcesbib:mamink,bib:markus 
equation 
eq:sourcemult 
J(x) = (x) + (x) - 2
^2 m(x) .
equation 
The effective action is then defined as the Legendre transform with respect
to these sources

equation 
  eq:effactdef 
    [J ,J  ] = ^4x   ( J(x) [W[ J] ]J(x)  +
  ) - W[J,J ] .
equation 
 are the classical fields ,
 and . As they shall transform linearly under
supersymmetry they can be combined to the chiral multiplet  of equation
eq:Phidef  (we suppress the index "cl" in the following). eq:effactdef  together with eq:sourcemult 
defines the unique effective action in terms of gauge-invariant and
supersymmetry covariant classical fields. In the thermodynamical limiting
process
align 
eq:thdyn 
  J   [J ,J  ] &= J(x) 0 & J(x)  W[J,J ]
  &= J (x) J align 
this effective action (or its effective potential resp.) lead per
definitionem to the true ground-state of the theory. Equation eq:thdyn 
has to be understood as a limiting process starting from a suitable UV and IR
regularization and performing the full non-perturbative
renormalization. During this process all  regularizations are getting
removed and the sources are finally relaxed to . The dual
parameters (classical fields) adopt their correct vacuum expectation values in
the limit.

Of course, we cannot perform these calculations explicitly. Thus certain assumptions enter in writing down equation
eq:effactdef  as discussed in
bergamin01  and references therein.

Our task is therefore to extend the action eq:vylagrangian  to a
non-local model, taking into account the important new features appearing
therein according to the discussion of the last section. This non-local action
is then seen as an ansatz for the quantum effective action
eq:effactdef .

To extend the model eq:vylagrangian  to a non-local Lagrangian we use
as starting-point the result of
bergamin02:1 . Therein the authors showed that the action
eq:localkahler  is -within the context of effective field theories- a
restricted form of a more general model, which is mandatory and of the form

equation 
  eq:nonlocalkahler 
    L  = ^4x   ( ^4    K(_n,
   _n) - (^2    W(_n) + ) ) .
equation 

The index  runs from zero to infinity, the defining field is 
 and the higher  are related to  by
align 
  eq:psincondition 
  _n &= D ^2  _n-1  , & _2n  &= (-1)^n ^n _0 , & _2n +1 
  &= (-1)^n ^n  _1 .
align 
Of course, the Lagrangian in eq:nonlocalkahler  could be formulated in terms of  and  alone  when
dropping the assumption that the Ka hler- and superpotential are
polynomials in , but are allowed to include explicit space-time
derivative terms. The corresponding action eq:intro1 

equation 
  eq:nlnonkahler 
  L  = ^4x   ( ^4    A(_0,_1 ,  _0,  _1) - (
  ^2    H(_0) + ) )
equation 

is actually more general than eq:nonlocalkahler . However, the effective
potential from eq:nonlocalkahler  and eq:nlnonkahler  are the
same, which is the quantity we are mostly interested in. The advantage of
eq:nonlocalkahler  is its simple mathematical form, but in certain
cases stability requirements
force us to add one term of order  that transgresses this
form (see section sec:consdyn  below).

The defining superfield of our model is the classical field  obtained from
Legendre transformation. Nevertheless it is difficult to implement all
symmetries when choosing . Standard superconformal transformations of a chiral
superfield imply that the mass dimension and
the  weight of such a  field obey the relation . Of course,
 is a correct chiral superfield in this sense, it has mass dimension 3
and chiral weight 2. But  has mass dimension 4 and
chiral weight 0. The field still has standard transformations under 
symmetry and scale transformations, but not under S-supersymmetry. Thus an
action in terms of  and  invariant under  and
scale transformations would not be invariant under S-supersymmetry.

We can escape these difficulties by observing that a chiral field  of the
form  transforms under S-supersymmetry with
dimension 2, regardless of the actual mass dimension of . If the true
dimension of  is not equal to 2, there appear additional anomalous
transformation terms. Thus we recover standard transformations under the full
superconformal group by choosing

align 
eq:thirdroot 
  _0 &= ()^1 3   .
align 

Of course, the third root of equation eq:thirdroot  has a threefold
multivaluedness. The consequential ambiguities in the invariant part of the
Lagrangian are the same as in eq:vylagrangian . Due to the relation
eq:thirdroot  the WZW-term of the actions eq:nonlocalkahler  and
eq:nlnonkahler  is restricted to the result found by Veneziano
and Yankielowicz, which does not show an ambiguity.

Ka hler and superpotential in eq:nonlocalkahler  are simply
polynomials in the fields  and thus we may write the invariant part of this
action as

align 
eq:kahlerexp 
  K(_n,  _n) &= _   _  (_0)^_0    (_)^_  ( _0)^ _0    ( _)^ _  , eq:suppotexp 
  W(_n) &= _  _  (_0)^_0    (_)^_  .
align 

The theory depends on infinitely many dimensionless coupling constants
 and . The vectors ,  and  are restricted to combinations
with correct mass dimension and  invariance:
align 
eq:kahlercond 
  _i (i+1) (_i +  _i) &= 2 & _i ( (_2i  -
   _2i ) + 2 (_2i+1  -
   _2i+1 )) &= 0 eq:suppotcond 
