The Veneziano-Yankielowicz Lagrangian 

The effective description of  SYM theories goes back to the work by
Veneziano and Yankielowicz. The authors showed that it is
possible to obtain a low energy description of the theory by means of an
effective Lagrangian in terms of the anomaly multiplet (also referred to as
Lagrangian or glue-ball multiplet)

 

In the present paper we extend this Lagrangian by adding higher
derivative terms and we show that this procedure changes the role of the local
part of in a non-trivial way. To make our statements more
transparent we shortly review the arguments leading to the Lagrangian of
ref. .

It is most natural to assume that the low-energy dynamics of confined SYM
theories must be described in terms of the anomaly multiplet . Indeed,
its lowest component is the gaugino-condensate, the spinor represents the
Goldstino if supersymmetry breaks dynamically and its highest component
contains the operators  and 
 used to represent the anomaly of the -current and
scale invariance. Also, this multiplet has a definite interpretation in the
underlying symmetry structure as it appears in the anomaly of the
supercurrent(This supercurrent in equation eq:anomcurrent  is
  not to be confused with the local current of the supercharge .) 

 

Thus we can expect that the multiplet  is defined not only in perturbation
theory but
also in the non-perturbative region. The effective description is obtained by
writing down the most general Lagrangian in terms of  having the correct
symmetry properties.  is gauge-invariant by construction and
supersymmetry is realized linearly as  is a chiral superfield. Thus the
most general Lagrangian has the form

 

The remaining symmetries are the anomalous -current, scale invariance and
special supersymmetry transformations (-supersymmetry). Correct
anomaly cancellation is obtained by a term 
with  being the scale of the theory
. Adding up all invariant terms that are
polynomial in the field , we
arrive at the Veneziano-Yankielowicz Lagrangian

 

Symmetries determine the Lagrangian up to four dimensionless constants ,
,  and the renormalized coupling constant of the fundamental theory,
. Performing the integrals over Grassman variables yields (
