As a consequence of (1) and (2)  has to be seen as an independent degree of freedom. At least in the
framework of effective actions it is possible to formulate consistent
supersymmetric actions of this type, where some important features
of supersymmetric theories with "normal" auxiliary fields are compromised. This especially
includes (see ref.  for a detailed discussion):

 
The full potential is not positive semi-definite: Obviously the
  positivity of the potential holds after elimination of the auxiliary fields,
  only. The statement that supersymmetric potentials are always positive
  semi-definite is actually a statement about the maximum of the auxiliary
  field potential: The latter is zero (unbroken supersymmetry) or positive
  (broken supersymmetry). As this maximum does no longer represent the ground
  state in a theory with dynamical "auxiliary" fields, the physical potential
  can have a negative minimum. This has important consequences in the
  discussion of supersymmetry breaking: In classical and perturbative
  supersymmetry a supersymmetric state (i.e. a state with vanishing potential) is automatically the ground-state and
  implies unbroken supersymmetry. In the non-perturbative region this
  conclusion does not hold, as the "auxiliary" fields become dynamical.
While the potential is not necessarily positive, the restriction on the
  vacuum energy still holds: 
 due to supersymmetry current-algebra relations. 
 implies supersymmetry breaking, while  means
  unbroken supersymmetry. In a strictly perturbative and/or semiclassical
  logic a strict relation between the minimum of the effective potential and
  the order parameter  exists:  due to the
  non-renormalization theorem. In a fully non-perturbative framework an
  extension of this relation to ,  but
   is possible. A consistent relation of this form can
  be achieved only by a non-perturbative extension of the trace anomaly
  eq:anomcurrent (In this paper we do not provide such an extension.) .
  But in any case the order parameter of
  supersymmetry breaking is still  and in the effective theory the
  latter is represented by the value of
   in the ground-state.
Supersymmetry breaks dynamically. Interestingly enough this follows directly
  from eq:vylagrangian  and eq:vyonshell : The unstable maximum
  is at the supersymmetry preserving point (vanishing potential and ). As the
  action eq:vylagrangian  is complete up to order
  , the unstable maximum cannot turn directly into
  a minimum (stability of  forbids to choose  in eq:vylagrangian ). Instead, the new minimum must be at a different value of :
  . But  is the order parameter of supersymmetry breaking and
  we arrive at the desired result. The argument of that
  supersymmetry is unbroken in  SYM thus turns into the opposite when
  taking into account all (including non-local) terms.







